{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b4653c11-a064-4772-83f6-7fda8ecf74ed","content":"PID 12345 isn't running on this machine, but here's how to diagnose and configure on your target system:\n\n## 1. Detect the runtime\n\n```bash\n# Check for CoreCLR shared libraries in the process\ngrep -q 'libcoreclr' /proc/12345/maps && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Likely NativeAOT\"\n\n# Alternatively, check if it links against libcoreclr\ncat /proc/12345/maps | grep -iE 'coreclr|libclrjit|libhostfxr'\n```\n\n**CoreCLR** processes load `libcoreclr.so`, `libclrjit.so`, `libhostfxr.so`.  \n**NativeAOT** binaries are self-contained with none of these — the binary *is* the runtime.\n\n## 2. Configure crash dumps\n\n### For CoreCLR apps\n\nSet environment variables (e.g. in your systemd unit or shell):\n\n```bash\n# Enable crash dumps\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\n\n# Dump type: 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4\n\n# Dump output path (%d = PID, %t = timestamp)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/var/dumps/coredump_%d_%t.dmp\n```\n\n### For NativeAOT apps\n\nNativeAOT doesn't use the managed dump infrastructure. Use the **OS-level core dump** mechanism instead:\n\n```bash\n# Set core dump pattern\necho '/var/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n\n# Remove core size limit for the process\nulimit -c unlimited\n\n# Or via systemd (recommended):\n# [Service]\n# LimitCORE=infinity\n```\n\nIf you use **systemd-coredump** (common on modern distros):\n\n```bash\n# Check if it's already active\ncoredumpctl list --no-pager | tail -5\n\n# Config: /etc/systemd/coredump.conf\n# [Coredump]\n# Storage=external\n# MaxUse=2G\n```\n\n## 3. Quick detection + setup script\n\n```bash\n#!/bin/bash\nPID=$1\nif grep -q 'libcoreclr' /proc/$PID/maps 2>/dev/null; then\n    echo \"CoreCLR detected — set DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1 in the app environment\"\nelse\n    echo \"NativeAOT (or non-.NET) — configure kernel core_pattern or systemd-coredump\"\nfi\n```\n\nRun the detection against your PID first, then apply the matching configuration. Want me to generate a ready-to-use systemd unit snippet for either case?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1b680178-8fff-470c-b211-e113961c4145","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine (PID 12345). That's expected — the user is asking for guidance, not necessarily running it here. Let me give them a comprehensive answer on how to detect the runtime and configure dumps accordingly.","outputTokens":771,"requestId":"6407:25EBA9:156A62C:18F1A16:69EC1AC4"},"id":"2bc180f9-8096-46aa-a6fe-972be6253d8b","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:37:26.794Z","parentId":"473aa6c9-5365-4c7b-b42a-f62b44eb5faa"}
